    slug: 'headless-commerce-migration-strangler-fig-session-state',
    title: 'Headless Commerce Migration: Solving Session Persistence in Strangler Fig Architectures',
    excerpt: 'A technical post-mortem on maintaining session integrity and cart state during a high-scale transition from legacy monoliths to Next.js.',
    date: '2026-03-30',
    readTime: '5 min read',
    category: 'Engineering Performance',
    author: 'FouriqTech Engineering',
    content: `
      <h1>Headless Commerce Migration: Orchestrating the Strangler Fig Pattern with <a href="/blog/nextjs-memory-leak-production-forensics">forensic post-mortem resolving</a> & Shared State</h1><p>Most technical guides for a <strong>monolith to headless commerce migration</strong> focus on the UI benefits while ignoring the catastrophic failure point: shared state persistence. During a recent replatforming for a global retailer (1.2M MAU, 450 RPS peak), we encountered a critical session synchronization failure that led to an 18% spike in cart abandonment within hours of deploying the first phased routes. This case study breaks down the architecture required to prevent state drift when orchestrating a Next.js frontend alongside a legacy SAP Commerce Cloud backend.</p><h2>1. INCIDENT REPORT: THE SESSION VOID</h2><p>The migration utilized the <a href="https://martinfowler.com/bliki/StranglerFigApplication.html">Strangler Fig Application</a> pattern, routing 30% of traffic (Product Detail Pages) to a Next.js instance while keeping the checkout flow on the legacy JSP monolith. Within 120 minutes of deployment, telemetry indicated a 22% failure rate in 'Add to Cart' actions for users transitioning between the new PDPs and the legacy checkout. The p95 latency for session hydration spiked from 110ms to 840ms, causing the Backend-for-Frontend (BFF) to timeout and return null session objects.</p><h2>2. WRONG ASSUMPTIONS</h2><p>Initial triage focused on cookie-domain configuration and SameSite attribute mismatches. We assumed the issue was a client-side browser rejection of the <code>JSESSIONID</code> when moving between the <code>shop.enterprise.com</code> (Next.js) and <code>checkout.enterprise.com</code> (Legacy) subdomains. However, logs showed the cookies were being sent correctly; the data within the session store simply didn't exist when requested by the secondary system.</p><h2>3. DEBUGGING PROCESS</h2><p>We implemented distributed tracing across the <strong>proxy-layer orchestration</strong> using OpenTelemetry. By injecting a <code>x-fouriq-trace-id</code>, we monitored the request lifecycle across three layers:</p><ul><li><strong>Cloudflare Workers:</strong> Acting as the routing proxy.</li><li><strong>Next.js BFF:</strong> Handling the <strong>API-first architecture</strong> calls.</li><li><strong>Redis:</strong> Serving as the shared session store between Java (Legacy) and Node.js (Next.js).</li></ul><p>We discovered that while Next.js was writing to Redis, the legacy Java monolith utilized a deferred write-back strategy. The legacy system only flushed session updates to the database at the end of the request lifecycle, creating a race condition where the Next.js app was reading stale or empty data before the legacy write had finalized.</p><h2>4. ROOT CAUSE</h2><p>The failure was a synchronization lag inherent in the <strong>data synchronization legacy</strong> adapters. The legacy monolith expected to be the exclusive owner of the session. When the Next.js BFF modified the session (e.g., adding an item), it updated Redis immediately. However, when the user clicked 'Checkout' (Legacy), the monolith would overwrite the Redis key with its own locally cached (and now stale) session data, effectively wiping the user's cart. This is the 'Lost Update' problem in a distributed environment.</p><h2>5. IMPLEMENTATION FIX: THE REDIS BRIDGE</h2><p>We moved away from a passive shared session to an active <strong>session synchronization</strong> layer. We implemented a centralized Session Bridge using a 'Write-Through' cache strategy in the Next.js middleware. To ensure the legacy monolith didn't overwrite new data, we introduced a versioning header in the Redis payload.</p><pre><code>// Next.js BFF Session Middleware Logic
export async function updateSession(sessionId, cartData) {
  const current = await redis.hgetall(\`session:\${sessionId}\`);
  const nextVersion = parseInt(current.version || 0) + 1;

  // Atomic update using Lua script to prevent race conditions
  const result = await redis.eval(LUA_LOCK_UPDATE, 1, sessionId, 
    JSON.stringify({ ...cartData, version: nextVersion }));

  if (!result) throw new Error('Session Lock Contention');
}</code></pre><p>This logic was coupled with a <strong>BFF pattern</strong> that acted as a translation layer, converting the legacy Java-serialized objects into clean JSON for the Next.js frontend. This improved the <a href="/blog/nextjs-bff-architecture-enterprise-microservices">Next.js BFF architecture</a> efficiency significantly.</p><h2>6. MEASURED RESULTS</h2><p>Following the architectural shift, the system stabilized with the following metrics:</p><ul><li><strong>Cart Persistence Success:</strong> 99.98% (up from 78%).</li><li><strong>p95 Session Hydration:</strong> 42ms (reduced from 840ms).</li><li><strong>TTFB (Edge Proxy):</strong> 28ms steady state.</li><li><strong>Headless Commerce ROI:</strong> 14% increase in mobile conversion rates due to sub-second page transitions.</li></ul><h2>7. UNEXPECTED PROBLEM: REDIS REPLICATION LAG</h2><p>After the fix, we noticed 'ghost carts' where items disappeared for 2-3 seconds and then reappeared. The root cause was Redis Global Data Replication. The session was written to <code>us-east-1</code>, but if the user's next request was routed to <code>eu-west-1</code> by the Global Server Load Balancer (GSLB) before replication finished, the session appeared empty. We mitigated this by enforcing regional affinity at the proxy level, pinning a session ID to a specific region for the duration of the <strong>incremental migration</strong> phase.</p><h2>8. REQUEST LIFECYCLE BREAKDOWN</h2><ol><li><strong>Edge Entry (0ms):</strong> Request hits Cloudflare; proxy determines route (Next.js vs Legacy).</li><li><strong>Middleware Execution (5-12ms):</strong> Next.js middleware extracts <code>SESSION_TOKEN</code> and performs a <code>GET</code> on the regional Redis cluster.</li><li><strong>Data Resolution (15-25ms):</strong> BFF fetches product data from the legacy API and merges it with the session cart state.</li><li><strong>Rendering (40-60ms):</strong> Next.js generates the React Server Components (RSC) payload.</li><li><strong>Response (65ms+):</strong> Final HTML/RSC stream sent to client with updated versioned session headers.</li></ol><h2>9. TRADE-OFF ANALYSIS</h2><p>This approach requires maintaining a high-availability Redis cluster across all active regions, increasing infrastructure overhead by approximately 12%. For smaller <strong>monolith to headless commerce migration</strong> projects, this complexity might be overkill. However, for enterprise scale, the alternative—losing cart state—is a direct hit to revenue that far exceeds server costs. This strategy is limited to approximately 150k concurrent sessions before Redis cluster sharding becomes mandatory to avoid I/O blocking.</p><h2>10. STRONG OPINION</h2><p>If your <strong>monolith to headless commerce migration</strong> strategy assumes that a shared cookie is enough to maintain state, you are designing for failure. Real-world commerce requires an authoritative, versioned state-bridge. At FouriqTech, we maintain that if your frontend cannot guarantee session integrity during a <a href="/blog/enterprise-legacy-system-<a href="/services/legacy-web-application-modernization">modernization</a>-strategy-nextjs-strangler-fig">legacy system <a href="/services/legacy-web-application-modernization">modernization</a></a>, the performance gains of Next.js are irrelevant. Architecture is about state management, not just fast pixels.</p>
